{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3ccde1cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# NVDA Volatility Predictability via PCA (Free OHLC Data)\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook builds an **aggregate volatility “state” factor** for NVIDIA (NVDA) using only daily OHLCV data and tests a specific hypothesis:\n",
    "\n",
    "**When the volatility state is high today, does realized variance tend to fall over the next _k_ trading days?**\n",
    "\n",
    "Scope:\n",
    "- Uses **price-based** (realized) volatility estimators computed from OHLC.\n",
    "- Tests predictability with an **out-of-sample** split and **HAC/Newey–West** standard errors.\n",
    "\n",
    "Limitations:\n",
    "- No implied volatility history, no option prices, no bid/ask, no theta/gamma.\n",
    "- This evaluates **signal predictability**, not options PnL.\n",
    "\n",
    "Data:\n",
    "- CSV with columns: `Date, Open, High, Low, Close, Volume`.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "afaaf2cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "Packages:\n",
    "- `pandas`, `numpy`: data + numerical work\n",
    "- `scikit-learn`: PCA\n",
    "- `statsmodels`: OLS regression with HAC/Newey–West standard errors\n",
    "- `matplotlib`: plotting\n",
    "\n",
    "Why HAC/Newey–West?\n",
    "If you model a **forward _k_-day change** each day, those windows overlap. Overlap causes autocorrelation in residuals; HAC adjusts standard errors so t-stats aren’t artificially inflated.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7e0222ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "import statsmodels.api as sm\n",
    "\n",
    "TRADING_DAYS = 252\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e5b0d35",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1) Load OHLCV data\n",
    "\n",
    "Set `CSV_PATH` to your OHLC CSV file. Recommended repo structure:\n",
    "\n",
    "- `data/nvda.us_d.csv`\n",
    "\n",
    "The loader supports comma-delimited files (common) and also works if the file is tab-delimited.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "52bd9816",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "CSV_PATH = \"data/nvda_us_d.csv\"  # included in this repo\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load CSV (supports comma-delimited; also works if the file is tab-delimited)\n",
    "df = pd.read_csv(CSV_PATH, sep=r\"\\t|,\", engine=\"python\")\n",
    "df.columns = [str(c).strip().lower() for c in df.columns]\n",
    "df = df.loc[:, [c for c in df.columns if not c.startswith(\"unnamed\")]]\n",
    "\n",
    "if \"date\" not in df.columns:\n",
    "    raise ValueError(f\"Expected a 'Date' column. Found: {df.columns.tolist()}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "df[\"date\"] = pd.to_datetime(df[\"date\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
    "df = df.dropna(subset=[\"date\"]).sort_values(\"date\").set_index(\"date\")\n",
    "\n",
    "for c in [\"open\",\"high\",\"low\",\"close\",\"volume\"]:\n",
    "    if c in df.columns:\n",
    "        df[c] = pd.to_numeric(df[c], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
    "\n",
    "df = df.dropna(subset=[\"open\",\"high\",\"low\",\"close\"]).copy()\n",
    "df[\"log_ret\"] = np.log(df[\"close\"]).diff()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Data range:\", df.index.min().date(), \"to\", df.index.max().date())\n",
    "df.head()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3f63f761",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2) Volatility feature engineering from OHLC\n",
    "\n",
    "We compute several **annualized** volatility estimators.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.1 Realized volatility (close-to-close)\n",
    "Let $r_t = \\log(C_t) - \\log(C_{t-1})$. For window length $n$:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "RV_n(t) = \\sqrt{252}\\;\\mathrm{Std}(r_{t-n+1:t})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.2 Parkinson volatility (range-based)\n",
    "Uses high/low range:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sigma^2_{P}(t) = \\frac{1}{4\\ln 2}\\left(\\ln\\frac{H_t}{L_t}\\right)^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "We take a rolling average of this daily variance, then annualize.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.3 Garman–Klass volatility (OHLC-based)\n",
    "A classic OHLC estimator combining the high–low range and open–close move.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.4 Yang–Zhang volatility (OHLC-based)\n",
    "Combines:\n",
    "- close-to-open variance (overnight)\n",
    "- open-to-close variance\n",
    "- Rogers–Satchell intraday variance  \n",
    "into a robust estimator.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2.5 EWMA volatility (RiskMetrics)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sigma_t^2 = \\lambda\\sigma_{t-1}^2 + (1-\\lambda)r_{t-1}^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "with $\\lambda\\approx 0.94$.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cc9e53eb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def realized_vol(log_ret, window):\n",
    "    return log_ret.rolling(window).std(ddof=0) * np.sqrt(TRADING_DAYS)\n",
    "\n",
    "def parkinson_vol(high, low, window):\n",
    "    rs = (np.log(high/low))**2\n",
    "    var = rs.rolling(window).mean() / (4*np.log(2))\n",
    "    return np.sqrt(var.clip(lower=0) * TRADING_DAYS)\n",
    "\n",
    "def garman_klass_vol(open_, high, low, close, window):\n",
    "    log_hl = np.log(high/low)\n",
    "    log_co = np.log(close/open_)\n",
    "    var_daily = 0.5*(log_hl**2) - (2*np.log(2)-1)*(log_co**2)\n",
    "    var = var_daily.rolling(window).mean()\n",
    "    return np.sqrt(var.clip(lower=0) * TRADING_DAYS)\n",
    "\n",
    "def yang_zhang_vol(open_, high, low, close, window):\n",
    "    log_oc = np.log(open_/close.shift(1))\n",
    "    log_co = np.log(close/open_)\n",
    "    log_ho = np.log(high/open_)\n",
    "    log_lo = np.log(low/open_)\n",
    "\n",
    "    rs = log_ho*(log_ho - log_co) + log_lo*(log_lo - log_co)\n",
    "\n",
    "    sigma_o2  = log_oc.rolling(window).var(ddof=0)\n",
    "    sigma_c2  = log_co.rolling(window).var(ddof=0)\n",
    "    sigma_rs  = rs.rolling(window).mean()\n",
    "\n",
    "    k = 0.34 / (1.34 + (window + 1)/(window - 1))\n",
    "    var = (sigma_o2 + k*sigma_c2 + (1-k)*sigma_rs)\n",
    "    return np.sqrt(var.clip(lower=0) * TRADING_DAYS)\n",
    "\n",
    "def ewma_vol(log_ret, lam=0.94):\n",
    "    r2 = (log_ret.fillna(0.0))**2\n",
    "    sigma2 = np.zeros(len(r2))\n",
    "    init = np.nanvar(r2.iloc[:60]) if len(r2) >= 60 else np.nanvar(r2)\n",
    "    sigma2[0] = init if np.isfinite(init) else 0.0\n",
    "    for i in range(1, len(r2)):\n",
    "        sigma2[i] = lam*sigma2[i-1] + (1-lam)*r2.iloc[i-1]\n",
    "    return pd.Series(np.sqrt(sigma2) * np.sqrt(TRADING_DAYS), index=log_ret.index)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Core feature set (kept small on purpose)\n",
    "df[\"rv20\"] = realized_vol(df[\"log_ret\"], 20)\n",
    "df[\"rv60\"] = realized_vol(df[\"log_ret\"], 60)\n",
    "df[\"par20\"] = parkinson_vol(df[\"high\"], df[\"low\"], 20)\n",
    "df[\"gk20\"]  = garman_klass_vol(df[\"open\"], df[\"high\"], df[\"low\"], df[\"close\"], 20)\n",
    "df[\"yz20\"]  = yang_zhang_vol(df[\"open\"], df[\"high\"], df[\"low\"], df[\"close\"], 20)\n",
    "df[\"ewma\"]  = ewma_vol(df[\"log_ret\"], lam=0.94)\n",
    "df[\"vov20\"] = df[\"rv20\"].rolling(20).std(ddof=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "features = [\"rv20\",\"rv60\",\"par20\",\"gk20\",\"yz20\",\"ewma\",\"vov20\"]\n",
    "X = df[features].dropna().astype(float)\n",
    "\n",
    "X.tail()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a55d9d26",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3) Rolling standardization (no lookahead)\n",
    "\n",
    "Volatility measures can have different scales. PCA works best when features are standardized.\n",
    "\n",
    "We compute rolling z-scores using only past data:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "z_t = \\frac{x_t - \\mu_{t}^{(W)}}{\\sigma_{t}^{(W)}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "where $\\mu_{t}^{(W)}$ and $\\sigma_{t}^{(W)}$ are the mean and std over the previous $W$ days.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4ec7606d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "PCA_WINDOW = 252  # ~1 trading year\n",
    "\n",
    "def rolling_zscore(s, window):\n",
    "    mu = s.rolling(window).mean()\n",
    "    sd = s.rolling(window).std(ddof=0)\n",
    "    return (s - mu) / sd\n",
    "\n",
    "Xz = X.copy()\n",
    "for c in Xz.columns:\n",
    "    Xz[c] = rolling_zscore(Xz[c], PCA_WINDOW)\n",
    "Xz = Xz.dropna()\n",
    "\n",
    "Xz.tail()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6db92466",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4) Rolling PCA to build the volatility state (PC1)\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA finds a linear combination of standardized features:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "PC1_t = w^\\top z_t\n",
    "$$\n",
    "where $w$ is chosen to maximize explained variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "To avoid lookahead:\n",
    "- Fit PCA on the **previous 252 days**.\n",
    "- Score today using the fitted component.\n",
    "\n",
    "Sign stability:\n",
    "PCA components are defined up to a sign. We align PC1 so that its loading on `RV20` is positive, so “higher PC1” consistently means “higher vol state”.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0425eb81",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### How PCA determines the loadings\n",
    "\n",
    "Let $Z \\in \\mathbb{R}^{n \\times p}$ be the matrix of **standardized** volatility features over the rolling window (rows = days, columns = features).\n",
    "\n",
    "PCA chooses weights $w$ so the projected series $Zw$ has maximal variance:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\max_{\\lVert w \\rVert = 1}\\ \\mathrm{Var}(Zw)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is equivalent to an eigenvector problem on the feature covariance matrix:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\Sigma = \\frac{1}{n-1} Z^\\top Z,\\qquad \\Sigma w = \\lambda w\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- **PC1 loadings** are the eigenvector $w_1$ associated with the **largest** eigenvalue $\\lambda_1$.\n",
    "- The **sign** of $w$ is arbitrary (both $w$ and $-w$ are valid), so we align the sign for consistent interpretation.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "75a553c6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def rolling_pca_pc1(Xz, window=252, anchor_col=\"rv20\"):\n",
    "    cols = list(Xz.columns)\n",
    "    anchor_idx = cols.index(anchor_col) if anchor_col in cols else 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    pc1 = pd.Series(index=Xz.index, dtype=float)\n",
    "    loadings_latest = None\n",
    "\n",
    "    vals = Xz.values\n",
    "    for i in range(window, len(Xz)):\n",
    "        train = vals[i-window:i]\n",
    "        pca = PCA(n_components=1)\n",
    "        pca.fit(train)\n",
    "\n",
    "        comp = pca.components_[0].copy()\n",
    "        if comp[anchor_idx] < 0:\n",
    "            comp *= -1  # align sign\n",
    "\n",
    "        pc1.iloc[i] = float(vals[i] @ comp)\n",
    "\n",
    "        if i == len(Xz) - 1:\n",
    "            loadings_latest = pd.Series(comp, index=cols, name=\"PC1_loading\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    return pc1.dropna(), loadings_latest\n",
    "\n",
    "pc1, pc1_loadings_latest = rolling_pca_pc1(Xz, window=PCA_WINDOW, anchor_col=\"rv20\")\n",
    "print(\"Latest PC1 loadings (sorted):\")\n",
    "print(pc1_loadings_latest.sort_values(ascending=False).round(4))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "01382bde",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.1 PC1 z-score (interpretability)\n",
    "PC1 is a factor score. A rolling z-score helps interpret “extreme” regimes:\n",
    "- PC1 z-score > 1: unusually high vol state\n",
    "- PC1 z-score < -1: unusually low vol state\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "13d517d9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Z_WINDOW = 60\n",
    "pc1_z = rolling_zscore(pc1, Z_WINDOW)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10,3))\n",
    "pc1_z.plot()\n",
    "plt.axhline(1.0, linestyle=\"--\")\n",
    "plt.axhline(-1.0, linestyle=\"--\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"PC1 z-score (rolling 60d)\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c4499344",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5) The predictability target: forward change in realized variance\n",
    "\n",
    "We test mean reversion of realized variance (variance = vol squared).\n",
    "\n",
    "Define:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_t = RV20^2(t+k) - RV20^2(t)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Interpretation:\n",
    "- $y_t < 0$: realized variance fell over the next $k$ days (mean reversion)\n",
    "- $y_t > 0$: realized variance rose\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "f0f9bed2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "K = 10  # horizon in trading days\n",
    "\n",
    "rv20 = df[\"rv20\"].reindex(pc1.index).dropna()\n",
    "idx = pc1.index.intersection(rv20.index)\n",
    "\n",
    "pc1 = pc1.loc[idx]\n",
    "pc1_z = pc1_z.loc[idx]\n",
    "rv20 = rv20.loc[idx]\n",
    "\n",
    "rv_var = rv20**2\n",
    "y = rv_var.shift(-K) - rv_var\n",
    "\n",
    "pd.DataFrame({\"PC1\": pc1, \"PC1_z\": pc1_z, \"RV20\": rv20, \"y\": y}).dropna().tail()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4da539f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6) Out-of-sample test with HAC/Newey–West errors\n",
    "\n",
    "Regression:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "y_t = a + b \\cdot PC1_t + \\epsilon_t\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "If $b < 0$, then high volatility state today predicts a decline in realized variance over the next $k$ days.\n",
    "\n",
    "Split:\n",
    "- DEV: dates <= 2019-12-31\n",
    "- TEST: dates >= 2020-01-01\n",
    "\n",
    "HAC/Newey–West:\n",
    "We set `maxlags = k` to account for overlap at horizon $k$.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e0e14cd0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "DEV_END = pd.to_datetime(\"2019-12-31\")\n",
    "TEST_START = pd.to_datetime(\"2020-01-01\")\n",
    "\n",
    "def hac_regression(y, x, maxlags):\n",
    "    X = sm.add_constant(x)\n",
    "    return sm.OLS(y, X, missing=\"drop\").fit(cov_type=\"HAC\", cov_kwds={\"maxlags\": maxlags})\n",
    "\n",
    "dev_mask = y.index <= DEV_END\n",
    "test_mask = y.index >= TEST_START\n",
    "\n",
    "dev_res = hac_regression(y[dev_mask], pc1[dev_mask], maxlags=K)\n",
    "test_res = hac_regression(y[test_mask], pc1[test_mask], maxlags=K)\n",
    "\n",
    "def coef_table(res):\n",
    "    out = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "        \"coef\": res.params,\n",
    "        \"t\": res.tvalues\n",
    "    })\n",
    "    return out\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"DEV (<=2019):\")\n",
    "display(coef_table(dev_res).round(4))\n",
    "print(\"\\nTEST (>=2020):\")\n",
    "display(coef_table(test_res).round(4))\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nInterpretation: PC1 slope < 0 supports mean reversion (high PC1 -> variance falls).\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "387d4139",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7) Nonlinear check: deciles in the TEST period\n",
    "\n",
    "A linear regression can miss a tail effect.  \n",
    "We bin TEST-period PC1 into 10 deciles and compute the average $y_t$ in each decile.\n",
    "\n",
    "If mean reversion is strongest in extremes, the highest deciles should have more negative average $y_t$.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "9097f8f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df_test = pd.DataFrame({\"pc1\": pc1, \"y\": y}).dropna()\n",
    "df_test = df_test[df_test.index >= TEST_START].copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "df_test[\"decile\"] = pd.qcut(df_test[\"pc1\"], 10, labels=False)\n",
    "decile_means = df_test.groupby(\"decile\")[\"y\"].mean()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8,3))\n",
    "decile_means.plot(kind=\"bar\")\n",
    "plt.title(f\"TEST: Mean future {K}D variance change by PC1 decile\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"PC1 decile (0=low vol state, 9=high vol state)\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(f\"E[ RV20^2(t+{K}) - RV20^2(t) ]\")\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "decile_means\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8f9a85e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8) Summary conclusions\n",
    "\n",
    "What you can claim from these tests:\n",
    "- PC1 is an interpretable **volatility regime factor** (based on loadings).\n",
    "- The sign and strength of mean reversion can be evaluated out-of-sample (DEV vs TEST).\n",
    "- Decile analysis shows whether mean reversion is concentrated in extremes.\n",
    "\n",
    "What you cannot claim from this:\n",
    "- Profitability of option selling (no implied vol, no options, no transaction costs).\n",
    "- A complete trading strategy.\n"
    "\n",
    "In the out-of-sample predictability test (k = 10 trading days, HAC/Newey–West errors), the relationship between the volatility state and future variance changes is negative in both periods, consistent with mean reversion.\n"
    "However, the effect is statistically strong in the DEV sample (<=2019) but not statistically convincing in the test sample (2020 and beyond). This suggests that while realized volatility mean reversion exists historically, its strength is not stable across regimes and may weaken in more recent data.\n"
    "The TEST-period decile analysis shows that the mean-reversion effect is more visible in the upper tail (extreme high-volatility states) than as a smooth linear relationship.\n"
    "Overall, this project supports using PC1 as an interpretable volatility regime factor and provides evidence of regime-dependent mean reversion in realized variance, but it does not establish a robust trading edge or an options-selling strategy without implied-vol/option data and execution modeling.\n"
   ]
  }
